<tales>
    <tale>
        <metadata>
            <title>Little Red Cap</title>
            <year>1812</year>
            <author>Jacob and Wilhelm Grimm</author>
            <language>English</language>
            <number>26</number>
        </metadata>
        <story>
            <p>Once upon a time there was a <character child-status="childless"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="little_red_cap">sweet little
                    girl</character>. <act agent="everyone" effect="benevolent"
                    receiver="litte_red_cap" type="being">Everyone who saw her liked her</act>, but
                most of all her <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="grandmother">grandmother</character>, who did not know what to give
                the child next. Once <act type="doing" receiver="little_red_cap" effect="benevolent"
                    agent="grandmother">she gave her a little cap made of red velvet</act>. Because
                it suited her so well, and she wanted to wear it all the time, she came to be known
                as <character reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried"
                    child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character>.</p>

            <p>One day <character child-status="mother" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="mother"/>her mother said to her, <dialogue speaker="mother"
                    stateofbeing="neutral">"Come <character reference="little_red_cap"
                        marital-status="unmarried" child-status="childless">Little Red
                        Cap</character>. Here is a piece of cake and a bottle of wine. Take them to
                    your grandmother. She is sick and weak, and they will do her well. Mind your
                    manners and give her my greetings. Behave yourself on the way, and do not leave
                    the path, or you might fall down and break the glass, and then there will be
                    nothing for your <character reference="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        child-status="grandmother">grandmother</character>. And when you enter her
                    parlor, don't forget to say 'Good morning,' and don't peer into all the corners
                    first."</dialogue></p>

            <p><dialogue stateofbeing="positive" speaker="little_red_cap">"I'll do everything just
                    right,"</dialogue> said <character reference="little_red_cap"
                    marital-status="unmarried" child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character>,
                    <act agent="little_red_cap" effect="benevolent" receiver="mother" type="doing"
                    >shaking her mother's hand.</act></p>

            <p>The <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="grandmother">grandmother</character>
                <act type="doing" effect="ambiguous" agent="grandmother">lived out in the
                    woods</act>, a half hour from the village. When <act agent="little_red_cap"
                    effect="ambiguous" type="doing"><character reference="little_red_cap"
                        marital-status="unmarried" child-status="childless">Little Red
                        Cap</character> entered the woods</act>
                <act type="doing" effect="ambiguous" agent="wolf">a wolf came up to her</act>. She
                did not know what a wicked animal he was, <act type="being" effect="ambiguous"
                    agent="little_red_cap">and was not afraid of him</act>.</p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="neutral">"Good day to you, <character
                        reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried"
                        child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character>."</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="little_red_cap" stateofbeing="neutral">"Thank you,
                    wolf."</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="neutral">"Where are you going so early,
                        <character reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried"
                        child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character>?"</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="little_red_cap" stateofbeing="neutral">"To <character
                        child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">grandmother's</character>."</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="neutral">"And what are you carrying under
                    your apron?"</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="little_red_cap" stateofbeing="neutral">"<act type="being"
                        effect="ambiguous" agent="grandmother"><character child-status="grandmother"
                            marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother"
                            >Grandmother</character> is sick and weak</act>, and <act
                        agent="little_red_cap" effect="benevolent" type="doing"
                        receiver="grandmother">I am taking her some cake and wine</act>. <act
                        agent="mother and little_red_cap" type="doing" effect="benevolent">We baked
                        yesterday</act>, and they should be good for her and give her
                    strength."</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p>
                <dialogue stateofbeing="negative" speaker="wolf">"<character
                        reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried"
                        child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character>, just where does your
                        <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">grandmother</character> live?"</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p><dialogue speaker="little_red_cap" stateofbeing="neutral">"Her house is good quarter
                    hour from here in the woods, under the three large oak trees. There's a hedge of
                    hazel bushes there. You must know the place,"</dialogue> said <character
                    reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried" child-status="childless"
                    >Little Red Cap</character>.</p>

            <p>The wolf thought to himself, "Now that <character reference="little_red_cap"
                    marital-status="unmarried" child-status="childless">sweet young
                    thing</character> is a tasty bite for me. She will taste even better than
                    <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="grandmother">the old woman</character>. You must be sly, and you can
                catch them both."</p>

            <p>He <act agent="wolf" effect="ambiguous" type="doing" receiver="little_red_cap">walked
                    along a little while with <character reference="little_red_cap"
                        marital-status="unmarried" child-status="childless">Little Red
                        Cap</character></act>, then he said, <dialogue speaker="wolf"
                    stateofbeing="negative">"<character reference="little_red_cap"
                        marital-status="unmarried" child-status="childless">Little Red
                        Cap</character>, just look at the beautiful flowers that are all around us.
                    Why don't you go and take a look? And I don't believe you can hear how
                    beautifully the birds are singing. You are walking along as though you were on
                    your way to school. It is very beautiful in the woods."</dialogue></p>

            <p><character reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried"
                    child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character>
                <act agent="little_red_cap" type="doing" effect="ambiguous">opened her eyes</act>
                and when <act agent="little_red_cap" type="doing" effect="benevolent">she saw the
                    sunbeams dancing to and fro through the trees and how the ground was covered
                    with beautiful flowers</act>, she thought, "If a take a fresh bouquet to
                    <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="grandmother">grandmother</character>, she will be very pleased.
                Anyway, it is still early, and I'll be home on time." And <act
                    agent="little_red_cap" effect="benevolent" type="doing">she ran off the path
                    into the woods looking for flowers</act>. Each time <act agent="little_red_cap"
                    type="doing" effect="benevolent">she picked one</act>
                <act agent="little_red_cap" type="doing" effect="benevolent">she thought that she
                    could see an even more beautiful one a little way off</act>, and <act
                    agent="little_red_cap" type="doing" effect="benevolent">she ran after it, going
                    further and further into the woods</act>. But the wolf ran straight to the
                    <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="grandmother">grandmother's</character> house and knocked on the
                door.</p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="grandmother" stateofbeing="neutral">"Who's there?"</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="negative">"<character
                        reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried"
                        child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character>. I'm bringing you some
                    cake and wine. Open the door."</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p><dialogue speaker="grandmother" stateofbeing="neutral">"Just press the
                    latch,"</dialogue> called out the <character marital-status="unmarried"
                    child-status="grandmother" reference="grandmother">grandmother</character>.
                    <dialogue speaker="grandmother" stateofbeing="negative">"I'm too weak to get
                    up."</dialogue></p>

            <p>The wolf pressed the latch, and the door opened. He stepped inside, went straight to
                the grandmother's bed, and <act agent="wolf" receiver="grandmother" effect="hostile"
                    type="doing">ate her up</act>. Then he put on her clothes, put her cap on his
                head, got into her bed, and pulled the curtains shut.</p>

            <p><character reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried"
                    child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character>
                <act type="doing" effect="benevolent" agent="little_red_cap">had run after the
                    flowers</act>. After <act type="doing" effect="benevolent"
                    agent="little_red_cap">she had gathered so many that she could not carry any
                    more</act>, <act type="doing" effect="benevolent" agent="little_red_cap">she
                    remembered her grandmother</act>, and then <act type="doing" effect="benevolent"
                    agent="little_red_cap" receiver="grandmother">continued on her way to her
                    house</act>. <act type="doing" effect="ambiguous" agent="little_red_cap">She
                    found, to her surprise, that the door was open</act>. <act type="doing"
                    effect="ambiguous" agent="little_red_cap">She walked into the parlor</act>, and
                everything looked so strange that she thought, <dialogue stateofbeing="negative"
                    speaker="little_red_cap">"Oh, my God, why am I so afraid? I usually like it at
                        <character marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother"
                        child-status="grandmother">grandmother's</character>."</dialogue></p>

            <p>She called out, <dialogue speaker="little_red_cap" stateofbeing="positive">"Good
                    morning!"</dialogue> but <act agent="little_red_cap" effect="ambiguous"
                    type="doing">received no answer.</act></p>

            <p>Then <act agent="little_red_cap" type="doing" effect="ambiguous">she went to the
                    bed</act> and <act agent="little_red_cap" type="doing" effect="ambiguous">pulled
                    back the curtains</act>. Grandmother was lying there with her cap pulled down
                over her face and looking very strange.</p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="little_red_cap" stateofbeing="negative">"Oh, grandmother, what
                    big ears you have!"</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="positive">"All the better to hear you
                    with."</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="little_red_cap" stateofbeing="negative">"Oh, grandmother, what
                    big eyes you have!"</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="positive">"All the better to see you
                    with."</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="little_red_cap" stateofbeing="negative">"Oh, grandmother, what
                    big hands you have!"</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="positive">"All the better to grab you
                    with!"</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="little_red_cap" stateofbeing="negative">"Oh, grandmother, what a
                    horribly big mouth you have!"</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="positive">"All the better to eat you
                    with!"</dialogue>
            </p>

            <p>The wolf had scarcely finished speaking when he jumped from the bed with a single
                leap and <act agent="wolf" type="doing" effect="hostile" receiver="little_red_cap"
                    >ate up poor <character reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried"
                        child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character></act>. As soon as the
                wolf had satisfied his desires, he climbed back into bed, fell asleep, and began to
                snore very loudly.</p>

            <p>A huntsman was just passing by. He thought, <dialogue speaker="huntsman"
                    stateofbeing="neutral">"The old woman is snoring so loudly. You had better see
                    if something is wrong with her."</dialogue></p>

            <p>He stepped into the parlor, and when he approached the bed, he saw the wolf lying
                there. <dialogue speaker="huntsman" stateofbeing="negative">"So here I find you, you
                    old sinner,"</dialogue> he said. <dialogue speaker="huntsman"
                    stateofbeing="negative">"I have been hunting for you a long
                time."</dialogue></p>

            <p>He was about to aim his rifle when it occurred to him that the wolf might have eaten
                the <character marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother"
                    child-status="grandmother">grandmother</character>, and that she still might be
                rescued. So instead of shooting, he took a pair of scissors and began to cut open
                the wolf's belly. After a few cuts he saw the red cap shining through., and after a
                few more cuts <character marital-status="unmarried" child-status="childless"
                    reference="little_red_cap">the girl</character>
                <act agent="little_red_cap" effect="ambiguous" type="doing">jumped out</act>,
                crying, <dialogue speaker="little_red_cap" stateofbeing="negative">"Oh, I was so
                    frightened! It was so dark inside the wolf's body!"</dialogue></p>

            <p>And then the <character marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother"
                    child-status="grandmother">grandmother</character>came out as well, alive but
                hardly able to breathe. Then <character reference="little_red_cap"
                    marital-status="unmarried" child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character>
                fetched some large stones. She filled the wolf's body with them, and when he woke up
                and tried to run away, the stones were so heavy that he immediately fell down
                dead.</p>

            <p>The three of them were happy. The huntsman skinned the wolf and went home with the
                pelt. The <character marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother"
                    child-status="grandmother">grandmother</character>
                <act agent="grandmother" type="doing" effect="benevolent">ate the cake and drank the
                    wine</act> that <character reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried"
                    child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character> had brought. And <character
                    reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried" child-status="childless"
                    >Little Red Cap</character> thought, <dialogue speaker="little_red_cap"
                    stateofbeing="neutral">"As long as I live, I will never leave the path and run
                    off into the woods by myself if mother tells me not to."</dialogue></p>

            <p>They also tell how <character reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried"
                    child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character> was <act
                    agent="little_red_cap" effect="ambiguous" type="doing" receiver="grandmother"
                    >taking some baked things to her <character marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother" child-status="grandmother">grandmother</character>
                    another time</act>, when <act agent="different_wolf" type="doing"
                    effect="hostile" receiver="little_red_cap">another wolf spoke to her and wanted
                    her to leave the path</act>. But <character reference="little_red_cap"
                    marital-status="unmarried" child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character>
                <act agent="little_red_cap" effect="ambiguous" type="doing">took care and went
                    straight to grandmother's</act>. <act agent="little_red_cap" effect="ambiguous"
                    type="doing" receiver="grandmother">She told her that she had seen the wolf, and
                    that he had wished her a good day, but had stared at her in a wicked
                    manner</act>. <dialogue speaker="little_red_cap" stateofbeing="negative">"If we
                    hadn't been on a public road, he would have eaten me up,"</dialogue> she
                said.</p>

            <p><dialogue speaker="grandmother" stateofbeing="neutral">"Come,"</dialogue> said the
                    <character marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother"
                    child-status="grandmother">grandmother</character>. <dialogue
                    speaker="grandmother" stateofbeing="neutral">"Let's lock the door, so he can't
                    get in."</dialogue></p>

            <p>Soon afterward the wolf knocked on the door and called out, <dialogue speaker="wolf"
                    stateofbeing="negative">"Open up, <character marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother" child-status="grandmother">grandmother</character>.
                    It's <character reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried"
                        child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character>, and I'm bringing you
                    some baked things."</dialogue></p>

            <p>They remained silent, and did not open the door. Gray-Head crept around the house
                several times, and finally jumped onto the roof. He wanted to wait until <character
                    reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried" child-status="childless"
                    >Little Red Cap</character> went home that evening, then follow her and eat her
                up in the darkness. But the <act agent="grandmother" effect="ambiguous" type="doing"
                    receiver="wolf"><character marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother"
                        child-status="grandmother">grandmother</character> saw what he was up
                    to</act>. There was a large stone trough in front of the house.</p>

            <p><dialogue speaker="grandmother" stateofbeing="neutral">"Fetch a bucket, <character
                        reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried"
                        child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character>,"</dialogue> she said to
                    <character reference="little_red_cap" child-status="childless"
                    marital-status="unmarried">the child</character>. <dialogue
                    stateofbeing="neutral" speaker="grandmother">"Yesterday I cooked some sausage.
                    Carry the water that I boiled them with to the trough."</dialogue>
                <act agent="little_red_cap" type="doing" effect="ambiguous"><character
                        reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried"
                        child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character> carried water until the
                    large, large trough was clear full</act>. The smell of sausage arose into the
                wolf's nose. He sniffed and looked down, stretching his neck so long that he could
                no longer hold himself, and he began to slide. He slid off the roof, fell into the
                trough, and drowned. And <act agent="little_red_cap" effect="benevolent"
                    type="doing"><character reference="little_red_cap" marital-status="unmarried"
                        child-status="childless">Little Red Cap</character> returned home
                    happily</act>, and no one harmed her.</p>
        </story>
    </tale>
    <tale>
        <metadata>
            <title>Rotkäppchen</title>
            <year>1821</year>
            <author>Jacob Grimm</author>
            <author>Wilhem Grimm</author>
            <language>German</language>
            <number>26</number>
        </metadata>
        <story>
            <p>Es war einmal eine kleine süße <character child-status="childless"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">Dirn</character>, die hatte jedermann
                lieb, der <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="red">sie</character> nur ansah, am al- lerliebsten aber ihre
                    <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character>, die wußte gar nicht, was
                    <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="grandmother">sie</character> alles dem <character
                    child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >Kind</character> geben sollte. Ein- mal schenkte <character
                    child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother"
                    >sie</character>
                <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >ihm</character> ein Käppchen von rothem Sammet, und weil <character
                    child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >ihm</character> das so wohl stand, und es nichts anders mehr tragen wollte,
                hieß <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >es</character> nur das Rothkäppchen; da sagte einmal seine <character
                    child-status="mother" marital-status="unmarried" reference="mother"
                    >Mutter</character> zu <character child-status="childless"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">ihm</character>: <dialogue
                    speaker="mother" stateofbeing="neutral">„komm, <character
                        child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                        >Rothkäppchen</character>, da hast <character child-status="childless"
                        marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">du</character> ein Stück Kuchen
                    und ein Bouteille mit Wein, die bring der Großmutter hinaus, <character
                        child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">sie</character> ist krank und schwach, da wird
                        <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">sie</character> sich daran laben; sey hübsch artig
                    und grüß <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="red">sie</character> von mir, geh auch ordentlich und lauf nicht
                    vom Weg ab, sonst fällst <character child-status="childless"
                        marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">du</character>, und zerbrichst
                    das Glas, dann hat die kranke <character child-status="grandmother"
                        marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character>
                    nichts.“</dialogue></p>

            <p><character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >Rothkäppchen</character> versprach der <character child-status="mother"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="mother">Mutter</character> recht gehorsam
                zu seyn. Die <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character> aber wohn- te draußen im Wald,
                eine halbe Stunde vom Dorf. Wie nun <character child-status="childless"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">Rothkäppchen</character> in den Wald
                kam, begegnete <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="red">ihm</character> der Wolf, <character child-status="childless"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">Rothkäppchen</character> aber wußte
                nicht, was das für ein böses Thier war, und fürchtete sich nicht vor ihm. <dialogue
                    speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="neutral">„Guten Tag, <character
                        child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                        >Rothkäppchen</character>.“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="red" stateofbeing="neutral">„Schön Dank Wolf.“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="neutral">„Wo willst <character
                        child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                        >du</character> so früh hinaus, <character child-status="childless"
                        marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">Rothkäpp-
                    chen</character>,“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="red" stateofbeing="neutral">„zur <character
                        child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character>.“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="neutral">„Was trägst <character
                        child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                        >du</character> unter der Schürze?“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="red" stateofbeing="neutral">„die <character
                        child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character> ist krank und schwach, da
                    bring ich <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">ihr</character> Kuchen und Wein, gestern haben wir
                    gebacken, da soll <character child-status="grandmother"
                        marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother">sie</character> sich
                    stärken.“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="neutral">„<character child-status="childless"
                        marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">Rothkäppchen</character>, wo
                    wohnt deine <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character>?“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="red" stateofbeing="neutral">„Noch eine gute Vier- telstunde im
                    Wald, unter den drei großen Eich- bäumen, da steht ihr Haus, unten sind die
                    Nußhecken das wirst du ja wissen“</dialogue> sagte <character
                    child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">Roth-
                    käppchen</character>. Der Wolf gedacht bei sich, das ist ein guter fetter Bissen
                für mich, wie fängst dus an, daß du den kriegst: <dialogue speaker="wolf"
                    stateofbeing="neutral">„hör <character child-status="childless"
                        marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">Rothkäpp- chen</character>, sagte
                    er, hast <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="red">du</character> die schönen Blumen nicht gesehen, die im
                    Walde stehen, warum guckst <character child-status="childless"
                        marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">du</character> nicht einmal um
                        <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="red">dich</character>, ich glaube, <character
                        child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                        >du</character> hörst gar nicht darauf, wie die Vöglein lieblich singen,
                        <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="red">du</character> gehst ja für <character
                        child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                        >dich</character> hin als wenn <character child-status="childless"
                        marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">du</character> im Dorf in die
                    Schule gingst, und ist so lustig haußen in dem Wald.“</dialogue></p>

            <p><character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >Rothkäppchen</character> schlug die Augen auf, und sah wie die Sonne durch die
                Bäume gebrochen war und alles voll schöner Blumen stand; da gedacht <character
                    child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >es</character>: ei! wenn ich der <character child-status="grandmother"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character> einen
                Strauß mitbringe, der wird <character child-status="grandmother"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother">ihr</character> auch lieb
                seyn, es ist noch früh, ich komm doch zu rechter Zeit an, und sprang in den Wald und
                suchte Blu- men. Und wenn <character child-status="childless"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">es</character> eine gebrochen hatte,
                meint <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >es</character>, dort stünd noch eine schönere und lief dar- nach und immer
                weiter in den Wald hinein. Der Wolf aber ging geradeswegs nach dem Haus der
                Großmutter und klopfte an die Thü- re. <dialogue speaker="grandmother"
                    stateofbeing="neutral">„Wer ist draußen“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="positive">„das <character
                        child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                        >Rothkäppchen</character>, ich bring <character child-status="grandmother"
                        marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother">dir</character> Kuchen
                    und Wein, mach mir auf.“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="grandmother" stateofbeing="negative">„Drück nur auf die Klinke,
                    rief die <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character>, ich bin zu schwach und kann
                    nicht aufstehen.“</dialogue> Der Wolf drückte an der Klinke, und die Thüre
                sprang auf. Da ging er hin- ein, geradezu an das Bett der <character
                    child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother"
                    >Großmutter</character> und <act type="doing" effect="hostile" agent="wolf"
                    receiver="grandmother">verschluckte <character child-status="grandmother"
                        marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother">sie</character></act>.
                Dann nahm er ihre Kleider, that <character child-status="grandmother"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother">sie</character> an, setzte
                sich ihre Haube auf, legte sich in ihr Bett und zog die Vorhänge vor.</p>

            <p><character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >Rothkäppchen</character> aber war herum gelaufen nach Blumen, und erst als
                    <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >es</character> so viel hatte, daß <character child-status="childless"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">es</character> keine mehr tragen
                konnte, machte <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="red">es</character> sich auf den Weg zu der <character
                    child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother"
                    >Großmutter</character>. Wie <character child-status="childless"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">es</character> ankam stand die Thüre
                auf, darüber verwunderte <character child-status="childless"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">es</character> sich, und wie
                    <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >es</character> in die Stube kam, sahs so seltsam darin aus, daß <character
                    child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >es</character> dacht: ei! du mein Gott wie ängstlich wird mirs heut zu Muth,
                und bin sonst so gern bei der <character child-status="grandmother"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character>. Drauf
                ging <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >es</character> zum Bett und zog die Vorhänge zurück, da lag die <character
                    child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother"
                    >Großmutter</character> und hatte die Haube tief ins Gesicht gesetzt und sah so
                wun- derlich aus. <dialogue speaker="red" stateofbeing="neutral">„Ei <character
                        child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character>, was hast <character
                        child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">du</character> für große Ohren!“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="positive">„daß ich <character
                        child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                        >dich</character> besser hö- ren kann.“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="red" stateofbeing="neutral">„Ei <character
                        child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character>, was hast <character
                        child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">du</character> für große Augen!“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="positive">„daß ich <character
                        child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                        >dich</character> besser se- hen kann.“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="red" stateofbeing="neutral">„Ei <character
                        child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character> was hast <character
                        child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">du</character> für große Hände!“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="positive">„daß ich <character
                        child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                        >dich</character> besser packen kann.“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="red" stateofbeing="neutral">„Aber <character
                        child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character>, was hast <character
                        child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">du</character> für ein entsetzlich großes
                    Maul!“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="negative">„daß ich <character
                        child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                        >dich</character> besser fressen kann.“</dialogue> Damit sprang der Wolf aus
                dem Bett, <act type="doing" effect="hostile" agent="wolf" receiver="red">sprang auf
                    das arme <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="red">Rothkäppchen</character></act>, und <act type="doing"
                    effect="hostile" agent="wolf" receiver="red">verschlang <character
                        child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                        >es</character>.</act></p>

            <p>Wie der Wolf den fetten Bissen erlangt hatte, legte er sich wieder ins Bett, schlief
                ein und fing an, überlaut zu schnarchen. Der Jä- ger ging eben vorbei und gedacht
                wie kann die alte <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="grandmother">Frau</character> so schnarchen, du mußt einmal nach-
                sehen. Da trat er hinein und wie er vors Bett kam, da lag der Wolf den er lange ge-
                sucht, der hat gewiß die <character child-status="grandmother"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character>
                gefressen vielleicht ist <character child-status="grandmother"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother">sie</character> noch zu
                retten, ich will nicht schießen, dachte der Jäger. Da nahm er die Scheere und
                schnitt ihm den Bauch auf, und wie er ein paar Schnitte gethan, da sah er das rothe
                    <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >Käppchen</character> leuchten, und wie er noch ein wenig geschnitten, da sprang
                das <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >Mädchen</character> her- aus und rief: <dialogue speaker="red"
                    stateofbeing="negative">„ach wie war ich erschrocken, was wars so dunkel in dem
                    Wolf seinem Leib;“</dialogue> und dann kam die <character
                    child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother"
                    >Großmutter</character> auch lebendig heraus. <character
                    child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >Rothkäppchen</character> aber holte große schwere Steine, damit füllten sie dem
                Wolf den Leib, und wie er aufwachte, wollte er fortspringen, aber die Steine waren
                so schwer, daß er sich todt fiel.</p>

            <p>Da waren alle drei vergnügt, der Jäger nahm den Pelz vom Wolf, die <character
                    child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother"
                    >Großmutter</character> aßden Kuchen und trank den Wein, den <character
                    child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">Roth-
                    käppchen</character> gebracht hatte, und <character child-status="childless"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">Rothkäppchen</character> ge- dacht
                bei sich: du willst dein Lebtag nicht wie- der allein vom Weg ab in den Wald laufen,
                wenn dirs die <character child-status="mother" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="mother">Mutter</character> verboten hat.</p>

            <p>Es wird auch erzählt, daß einmal, als <character child-status="childless"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">Roth- käppchen</character> der alten
                    <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character> wieder Gebacke- nes brachte, ein
                anderer Wolf ihm zugesprochen und es vom Weg ableiten wollen. <character
                    child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">Rothkäpp-
                    chen</character> aber hütete sich und ging gerad fort ihres Wegs, und sagte der
                    <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character> daß <character
                    child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother"
                    >sie</character> den Wolf gesehen, daß er ihm guten Tag gewünscht aber so bös
                aus den Augen geguckt; <dialogue speaker="red" stateofbeing="negative">„wenns nicht
                    auf offner Straße gewesen, er hätt mich gefressen.“</dialogue>
                <dialogue speaker="grandmother" stateofbeing="neutral">„Komm, sagte die <character
                        child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character> wir wollen die Thüre
                    verschließen, daß er nicht herein kann.“</dialogue> Bald darnach klopfte der
                Wolf an und rief: <dialogue speaker="wolf" stateofbeing="positive">„mach auf,
                        <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                        reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character>, ich bin das <character
                        child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                        >Rothkäppchen</character>, ich bring <character child-status="grandmother"
                        marital-status="unmarried" reference="grandmother">dir</character>
                    Gebackenes.“</dialogue> Sie schwiegen aber still und machten die Thüre nicht
                auf, da ging der Böse etlichemal um das Haus und sprang endlich aufs Dach, und
                wollte warten bis <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="red">Rothkäppchen</character> Abends nach Haus ging, dann wollt' er
                    <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >ihm</character> nachschleichen und wollts in der Dunkelheit fressen. Aber die
                    <character child-status="grandmother" marital-status="unmarried"
                    reference="grandmother">Großmutter</character> merkte, was er im Sinn hatte; da
                stand vor dem Haus ein großer Steintrog: <dialogue speaker="grandmother"
                    stateofbeing="neutral">„hol' den Eimer, <character child-status="childless"
                        marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">Rothkäppchen</character>, gestern
                    hab ich Würste gekocht, da trag das Wasser, worin <character
                        child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                        >sie</character> gekocht sind, in den Trog.“</dialogue>
                <character child-status="childless" marital-status="unmarried" reference="red"
                    >Rothkäppchen</character> trug so lange bis der große, große Trog ganz voll war.
                Da stieg der Geruch von den Wür- sten dem Wolf in die Nase, er schnupperte und
                guckte hinab, endlich machte er den Hals so lang, daß er sich nicht mehr halten
                konnte, er fing an zu rutschen, und rutschte vom Dach herab und gerade in den großen
                Trog hinein und ertrank. <character child-status="childless"
                    marital-status="unmarried" reference="red">Rothkäppchen</character> aber ging
                fröhlich und sicher nach Haus.</p>
